<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-561-164  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 561 164.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  August 21 1989 v8 n17 p36(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Price drop seen for fiber optics.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Olsen, Florence.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsPrice CuttingStandardsLocal Area NetworksFiber Distributed Data Interface Standard.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Price Drop Seen For Fiber OpticsandM;Not until the price premium for fiber cable levels off at 2-to-1 comparedwith Ethernet will high-speed, fiber-optic networks enjoy a higher profile ingovernment and industry circles, a fiber industry executive said recently.andM;By 1990, however, the price of fiber-optic components will be moreaffordable, said Mike Hartmann, digital interface products director for PCOInc., Chatsworth, Calif.andM;Hartmann said one step in that direction is PCO's recent agreement with ATandamp;TCo.'s Microelectronics Division to market identical digital fiber-optictransmitters and receivers that conform to Fiber Distributed Data Interface(FDDI) standards, Hartmann said.andM;By promoting a set of common characteristics for key FDDI components, ATandamp;Tand PCO officials hope to encourage government and industry to buyfiber-optic local area networks, said ATandamp;T Co. official Mark Melliar-Smith.andM;&quot;The ATandamp;T-PCO agreement is a step in providing customers with second-sourcingof key components that will speed acceptance of the FDDI LAN standard,&quot; saidRobert Walker, vice president of marketing for PCO.andM;PCO, a jointly owned subsidiary of Corning Glass Works, Corning, N.Y., andIBM Corp., manufactures optical products, including laser emitters and LEDs,and digital fiber-optic transceivers and transmitters.andM;Hartmann and Melliar-Smith spoke at a recent fiber optics seminar inWashington.andO;</TEXT></DOC>